# Database timestamp format

When persisting **human-readable** timestamps (text / JSON fields, audit payloads, activity strings), use the project standard format:

**Example:** `Jul 3, 2026, 2:56:58 PM CDT`

- Abbreviated month, day, year, comma, 12-hour time with seconds, AM/PM, and timezone abbreviation
- **No milliseconds**
- **No ISO-8601** (`2026-07-03T14:56:58.123-05:00`) in stored user-facing fields

## PostgreSQL

Use `api.format_activity_timestamp(date_trunc('second', p_ts))` — do not hand-roll `to_char` patterns.

```sql
-- TIMESTAMPTZ column (normal row audit / ORM-style)
modified_date := date_trunc('second', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP);

-- Text or JSON value shown to users
additional_info_json := jsonb_set(
  COALESCE(additional_info_json, '{}'::jsonb),
  '{last-activity}',
  to_jsonb(api.format_activity_timestamp(date_trunc('second', v_now)))
);
```

Parse stored values with `api.parse_activity_timestamp(text)` (supports ISO, new format, and legacy `... at ...` strings).

## Frontend

When writing readable timestamp strings to the API or formatting audit/activity display, use `formatReadableDateTime()` from `front-ends/front-end-cursor/src/utils/auditTimestamps.ts` — same visual format as the SQL helper.

## Do not

- Store raw `NOW()` / `CURRENT_TIMESTAMP` cast to text in JSON
- Use `toLocaleString()` ad hoc with different options
- Include fractional seconds in saved values
